# No Native Browser Dialogs

The browser-native `window.confirm`, `window.alert`, and `window.prompt` are
**banned** in this codebase. They:

- Cannot be styled to match dark mode or our theme.
- Are blocking and cause poor UX on mobile.
- Cannot render rich content (line breaks, lists, formatted descriptions).
- Look like a system pop-up rather than part of the app.

## Use the global lightbox dialog API instead

All confirmations, alerts, and text prompts must use the imperative API in
`@/components/ui/global-dialogs`. The `<GlobalDialogHost />` is mounted once
in `app/layout.tsx`, so any client component can call the helpers directly
and `await` the user's response.

### Examples

Confirm before a destructive action:

```tsx
import { confirmDialog } from "@/components/ui/global-dialogs";

async function handleDelete(row: { id: string; label: string }) {
  const ok = await confirmDialog({
    title: `Delete "${row.label}"?`,
    description: "This cannot be undone.",
    confirmLabel: "Delete",
    destructive: true,
  });
  if (!ok) return;
  await fetch(`/api/items/${row.id}`, { method: "DELETE" });
}
```

Show an info message:

```tsx
import { alertDialog } from "@/components/ui/global-dialogs";

await alertDialog({
  title: "Saved",
  description: "Your changes were saved successfully.",
});
```

Ask for a value:

```tsx
import { promptDialog } from "@/components/ui/global-dialogs";

const newName = await promptDialog({
  title: "Rename template",
  defaultValue: row.label,
  placeholder: "Enter a new name…",
});
if (!newName) return; // user cancelled or cleared the input
```

### Rules

1. **Never** call `window.confirm`, `window.alert`, or `window.prompt`
   (or the global `confirm` / `alert` / `prompt` shortcuts) anywhere in
   `app/`, `components/`, `lib/`, or any other workspace code. This is
   enforced as a hard rule — replace with the helpers above.

2. Use **`destructive: true`** on `confirmDialog` for delete / wipe / reset
   actions so the confirm button renders in red.

3. Keep `description` strings human-readable. The host renders descriptions
   with `whitespace-pre-line`, so `\n` becomes a real line break — use it
   for multi-line context (what will change, what is preserved, whether
   the action is reversible).

4. Always `await` the helper. Each call returns a Promise, and the dialog
   queues if another one is already open. Never fire-and-forget.

5. The host is mounted only once in `app/layout.tsx`. Do **not** mount
   another `<GlobalDialogHost />` anywhere else.

6. For truly modal flows that need richer content (multi-step forms,
   pickers, custom layouts), build a dedicated `<Dialog>` from
   `@/components/ui/dialog` and manage its `open` state locally — but for
   any plain yes/no / OK / single-input prompt, **use the helpers**.

### What to do when you see a violation

When editing a file that still uses `window.confirm` / `alert` / `prompt`,
migrate it as part of the same change:

```tsx
// Before
if (!window.confirm("Delete this row?")) return;

// After
import { confirmDialog } from "@/components/ui/global-dialogs";
const ok = await confirmDialog({
  title: "Delete this row?",
  confirmLabel: "Delete",
  destructive: true,
});
if (!ok) return;
```

Don't introduce regressions: the rest of the surrounding logic must stay
identical (same downstream branches, same error handling).
